post_text: ATTN: The P-EBT program has been extended. If you did not apply over the summer, now is your time to submit an application. Be sure to select your district as "Educators for Quality Alternatives", and then select the school site. Connect with your campus for assistance.
shared_text:
Louisiana Department of Education
September 8 at 1:30 PM ·

Louisiana is reopening the Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) program for families who did not apply in May and June. Families of children who receive free or reduced-price school meals may be eligible to receive financial benefits for meals missed in 2019-2020 when schools closed due to the pandemic. Apply from September 8 at 8 a.m. to September 29 at 5 p.m. These one-time benefits total $285 per child of families who were eligible for free and reduced-price meals during the entire closure last spring. Parents who started receiving free and reduced-price school meals in May will receive $91.20 per eligible child. The online application is simple. The information submitted must exactly match the information on file with the school system in order for the application to successfully submit. #louisianabelieves

https://pebt.doe.louisiana.gov/PublicApps/SNP/

ATTN: New Orleans educators and administrators.

Do you need assistance with a middle school student who is struggling? The Bridge is here to support YOU. Our dedicated team can assist you in locating a student who isn't engaging in instruction, provide on-campus support with academic and counseling services, or provide in-home support with counseling or academic needs.

Fill out the request form at https://bit.ly/31QD4dJ and we will be in touch to help you and your student.

This is a free service provided to New Orleans Public School students and our partners in education.

Starting tomorrow, 8/28, we will no longer be serving meals at NOAH or The NET: Gentilly.

Currently there are two options for EQA students to receive free meal service:

- Meals can be picked up from Samuel J. Green Charter School (2319 Valence St) or Arthur Ashe Charter School (1456 Gardena Dr) Mon, Wed, and Fri 12pm-3pm

- Families are also encouraged to utilize the City’s COVID-19 Meal Assistance Program. Families may be eligible to receive lunch and dinner meals delivered to their homes from local restaurants. Interested participants can register online at: nola311.org/MealAssist or by calling 3-1-1 (or 504-658-2299).
Please click here for the latest updates on meal service plans from NOLA Public Schools.

If you or your family would like to learn more about EQA's food pantry program, please reach out to Ms. Kim Legaux (klegaux@eqaschools.org) for more information.

In response to school disruptions due to COVID-19, The Bridge Middle School is temporarily serving as a free “Rapid Response Program" for NOLA-PS schools with 7th and 8th grade students. The Bridge is able to support students who are profoundly struggling during virtual learning and restricted capacity school models. These services are to support, not replace, virtual learning services offered by schools across the city. The purpose of this initiative is to connect students with the support needed to successfully complete the semester with their home school. #nolapublicschools #middleschool

Information session for school leaders on Wednesday. Check the site for details on the Zoom meeting.

Rental and Utility Assistance is available.

Has your family's finances been impacted by the #covid pandemic? If so, help is available to you. The Finance Authority of New Orleans has created a Community Support Fund to help families affected by COVID-19. They are providing Orleans Parish residents with up to $500 in rental assistance per household and $75 per household in utility assistance to those who meet their criteria.

To apply for FANO’s assistance, residents should call (504) 524-5533, (504) 354-0904, or email: csf@financeauthority.org.

post_text:
Great news! The NET Gentilly is a YouthForce NOLA Collaborative Partner High School for the 2020-21 school year! Our school and YouthForce NOLA believe that all of our students have the potential to live happy, prosperous lives -- and we want to connect all of our young people with the career skills, network, and knowledge needed to be successful. YouthForce NOLA is building a pathway for career and life success that we believe all students can utilize to build real-world skills to produce real-life success.

This includes job-specific credentials and soft skills growth, and connecting students with real career experiences that set them up for success, including virtual job site visits and internships.

post_text: Thanks to the leadership of Mayor LaToya Cantrell, the New Orleans Recreation Development (NORD) Commission and the New Orleans Public Library (NOPL) are launching community learning hubs. These spaces will provide youth with access to the internet (as well as devices in some locations) and offer enrichment activities based on age group and host site. Students will be grouped into small cohorts, with no more than 10 people in a space. Strict safety protocols will be followed including a mask requirement and social distancing.The program will be free and first-come, first-serve. Signup by calling the Office of Youth & Families at 504-295-5052 or by filling out this form: https://forms.gle/kR869PmbbLA1QbD1A

post_text:
Additional EBT Benefits available for families in LA with students receiving free or reduced lunches.

Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, students have been out of the school building without daily access to the food and nutrition services of the school system.

As of today, the State of Louisiana has authorized additional EBT benefits of $285 per child.

Families must complete the online application in order to receive a P-EBT card. This EBT card will function like a standard EBT card and this card will not affect any existing benefits the family receives.

For more information or to apply visit the DCFS website linked below.

The application portal opens on Monday, May 18 (today) and all applications must be submitted by June 8 (the portal is closing on that date).

post_text:
Congratulations to Brian Davis (Class of Fall 2013) for his new job at Cafe Reconcile!

Brian starred in the very first short films produced by The NET's Lights Camera Action class and was known around school as a friendly young man who was always willing to help out other students. After graduating from The NET, Brian completed Reconcile's job training program and secured employment at The Ashe Cultural Arts Center. He joins Reconcile full-time thanks to a grant from from the W.K. Kellogg Foundation.

Go Brian!
